edu.uw.cs.cse461.util

Class SampledStatistic.TransferRate

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.uw.cs.cse461.util.SampledStatistic.TransferRate
  • Enclosing class:
    SampledStatistic

    public static class SampledStatistic.TransferRate
extends Object
    Class to simplify making transfer rate measurements. Basically, call ElapsedTime.start("foo") at the beginning of a block of code and then ElapsedTime.stop("foo") at the end of the block to create an elapsed time sample associated with key "foo". (If some unusual condition occurs after calling start(), you can/must call ElapsedTime.abort("foo") to cancel the current measurement.)
    Author:
    zahorjan

      • start

        public static void start(String key)
        Indicate the start of an elapsed time interval. The interval should be terminated by calling stop() or abort().
        Parameters:
        key - The arbitary name of a timer (e.g., ElapsedTime.start("foo")).

      • stop

        public static double stop(String key,
          long dataAmount)
        Indicate that an elapsed time sample should be taken. The sample is the time that has passed since the last start() call with the name timer name (the argument key). It is an error to call stop if there has been no corresponding call to start.
        Parameters:
        key - The name of the timer with which to record the new elapsed time sample.
        dataAmount - The amount of data transfered during this interval.
        Returns:
        The length of the measured interval, in msec.

      • abort

        public static double abort(String key,
           long dataAmount)
        Indicates that the elapsed time since start() was called is no longer of interest, and so no new sample should be generated by ending the measurement interval. This might happen, for instance, if some exceptional condition occurs. Note that it is not an error to abort a timer that hasn't been started. (This makes it easier to catch errors over a long code sequence, as you don't have to keep track of just which timers have and which haven't yet been started.)
        Parameters:
        key - The name of a timer.
        Returns:
        The length of the measured interval, in msec.
